#: ../../source/debugger.rst:4
msgid "Debugging"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:6
msgid ""
"There are two main ways to debug Modelica code, the `transformations "
"browser <transformations-browser>`_, which shows the transformations "
"OpenModelica performs on the equations. There is also a debugger for "
":ref:`debugging of algorithm sections and functions <algorithm-"
"debugging>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:14
msgid "The Equation-based Debugger"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:16
msgid ""
"This section gives a short description how to get started using the "
"equation-based debugger in OMEdit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:20
msgid "Enable Tracing Symbolic Transformations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:22
msgid ""
"This enables tracing symbolic transformations of equations. It is "
"optional but strongly recommended in order to fully use the debugger. The"
" compilation time overhead from having this tracing on is less than 1%, "
"however, in addition to that, some time is needed for the system to write"
" the xml file containing the transformation tracing information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:28
msgid ""
"Enable -d=infoXmlOperations in Tools->Options->Simulation (see section "
":ref:`omedit-options-simulation`) OR alternatively click on the checkbox "
"*Generate operations in the info xml* in Tools->Options->Debugger (see "
"section :ref:`omedit-options-debugger`) which performs the same thing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:33
msgid ""
"This adds all the transformations performed by OpenModelica on the "
"equations and variables stored in the model\\_info.xml file. This is "
"necessary for the debugger to be able to show the whole path from the "
"source equation(s) to the position of the bug."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:39
msgid "Load a Model to Debug"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:41
msgid ""
"Load an interesting model. We will use the package `Debugging.mo "
"<https://github.com/OpenModelica/OMCompiler/blob/master/Examples/Debugging.mo>`__"
" since it contains suitable, broken models to demonstrate common errors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:45
msgid "Simulate and Start the Debugger"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:47
msgid ""
"Select and simulate the model as usual. For example, if using the "
"Debugging package, select the model "
"Debugging.Chattering.ChatteringEvents1. If there is an error, you will "
"get a clickable link that starts the debugger. If the user interface is "
"unresponsive or the running simulation uses too much processing power, "
"click cancel simulation first."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:56
msgid "Simulating the model."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:59
msgid "Use the Transformation Debugger for Browsing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:61
msgid ""
"Use the transformation debugger. It opens on the equation where the error"
" was found. You can browse through the dependencies (variables that are "
"defined by the equation, or the equation is dependent on), and similar "
"for variables. The equations and variables form a bipartite graph that "
"you can walk."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:67
msgid ""
"If the -d=infoXmlOperations was used or you clicked the “generate "
"operations” button, the operations performed on the equations and "
"variables can be viewed. In the example package, there are not a lot of "
"operations because the models are small."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:72
msgid ""
"Try some larger models, e.g. in the MultiBody library or some other "
"library, to see more operations with several transformation steps between"
" different versions of the relevant equation(s). If you do not trigger "
"any errors in a model, you can still open the debugger, using File->Open "
"Transformations File (model\\_info.json)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:80
msgid "Transfomations Browser."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:85
msgid "The Algorithmic Debugger"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:87
msgid ""
"This section gives a short description how to get started using the "
"algorithmic debugger in OMEdit. See section :ref:`omedit-options-"
"simulation` for further details of debugger options."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:92
msgid "Adding Breakpoints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:94
msgid "There are two ways to add the breakpoints,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:96
msgid ""
"Click directly on the line number in Text View, a red circle is created "
"indicating a breakpoint as shown in :numref:`omedit-add-breakpoint`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:99
msgid ""
"Open the Algorithmic Debugger window and add a breakpoint using the right"
" click menu of Breakpoints Browser window."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:105
msgid "Adding breakpoint in Text View."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:108
msgid "Start the Algorithmic Debugger"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:110
msgid ""
"You should add breakpoints before starting the debugger because sometimes"
" the simulation finishes quickly and you won’t get any chance to add the "
"breakpoints."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:114
msgid "There are four ways to start the debugger,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:116
msgid ""
"Open the Simulation Setup and click on Launch Algorithmic Debugger before"
" pressing Simulate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:119
msgid ""
"Right click the model in Libraries Browser and select Simulate with "
"Algorithmic Debugger."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:122
msgid ""
"Open the Algorithmic Debugger window and from menu select Debug-> :ref"
":`omedit-debug-configurations`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:125
msgid ""
"Open the Algorithmic Debugger window and from menu select Debug-> :ref"
":`omedit-debug-attach`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:131
msgid "Debug Configurations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:133
msgid ""
"If you already have a simulation executable with debugging symbols "
"outside of OMEdit then you can use the Debug->Debug Configurations option"
" to load it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:137
msgid ""
"The debugger also supports MetaModelica data structures so one can debug "
"omc executable. Select omc executable as program and write the name of "
"the mos script file in Arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:143
msgid "Debug Configurations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:148
msgid "Attach to Running Process"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:150
msgid ""
"If you already have a running simulation executable with debugging "
"symbols outside of OMEdit then you can use the Debug->Attach to Running "
"Process option to attach the debugger with it. :numref:`omedit-attach-to-"
"process` shows the Attach to Running Process dialog. The dialog shows the"
" list of processes running on the machine. The user selects the program "
"that he/she wish to debug. OMEdit debugger attaches to the process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:160
msgid "Attach to Running Process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:163
msgid "Using the Algorithmic Debugger Window"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:165
msgid ""
":numref:`omedit-algorithmic-debugger` shows the Algorithmic Debugger "
"window. The window contains the following browsers,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:168
msgid ""
"*Stack Frames Browser* – shows the list of frames. It contains the "
"program context buttons like resume, interrupt, exit, step over, step in,"
" step return. It also contains a threads drop down which allows switching"
" between different threads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:173
msgid ""
"*BreakPoints Browser* – shows the list of breakpoints. Allows "
"adding/editing/removing breakpoints."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:176
msgid ""
"*Locals Browser* – Shows the list of local variables with values. Select "
"the variable and the value will be shown in the bottom right window. This"
" is just for convenience because some variables might have long values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:181
msgid ""
"*Debugger CLI* – shows the commands sent to gdb and their responses. This"
" is for advanced users who want to have more control of the debugger. It "
"allows sending commands to gdb."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:185
msgid "*Output Browser* – shows the output of the debugged executable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/debugger.rst:190
msgid "Algorithmic Debugger."
msgstr ""

